The '''Immunome''' is the set of the [[gene|genes]] and [[protein|proteins]] that constitute the [[immune system]].<ref name="MyUser_Iavireport.org_April_25_2016c">{{cite web |url=http://www.iavireport.org/Back-Issues/Pages/Prepping-for-the-Immunome.aspx |title=IAVI Report - Prepping for the Immunome |newspaper=Iavireport.org |date=  |author= |accessdate= April 25, 2016}}</ref> Typically, immunomes are studied using [[immunofluorescence]] microscopy to determine the presence and activity of immune-related [[enzyme|enzymes]] and pathways.<ref name="MyUser_Ncbi.nlm.nih.gov_April_25_2016c">{{cite journal |title=Studying the Human Immunome: The Complexity of Comprehensive Leukocyte Immunophenotyping |pmc=4184245 | pmid=23975032 |doi=10.1007/82_2013_336 |volume=377 |year=2014 |journal=Curr. Top. Microbiol. Immunol. |pages=23–60 | last1 = Biancotto | first1 = A | last2 = McCoy | first2 = JP}}</ref>

